[
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm trying to figure out how to elegantly achieve the following in rust, i.e. pass C functions as callbacks:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Rust\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">const</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">struct</span> <span class=\"nc\">file_operations</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">erofs_dir_fops</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"err\">»·······</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">llseek</span><span class=\"err\">»»·······</span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">generic_file_llseek</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"err\">»·······</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">read</span><span class=\"err\">»··»·······</span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">generic_read_dir</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"err\">»·······</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">iterate_shared</span><span class=\"err\">»</span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">erofs_readdir</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">};</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Here, <code>generic_file_llseek</code> and <code>generic_read_dir</code> are some generic C functions and <code>erofs_readdir</code> is implemented specifically for the <code>erofs</code> filesystem. I would like to be able to do the same in rust, specify generic functions for some callbacks and implement some other functions in rust.<br>\nOn the rust side, I have:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Rust\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">const</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">VTABLE</span>: <span class=\"nc\">bindings</span>::<span class=\"n\">file_operations</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">bindings</span>::<span class=\"n\">file_operations</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"n\">open</span>: <span class=\"nb\">Some</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"bp\">Self</span>::<span class=\"n\">open_callback</span><span class=\"p\">),</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"n\">release</span>: <span class=\"nb\">Some</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"bp\">Self</span>::<span class=\"n\">release_callback</span><span class=\"p\">),</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"n\">read</span>: <span class=\"nc\">if</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">T</span>::<span class=\"n\">HAS_READ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"nb\">Some</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"bp\">Self</span>::<span class=\"n\">read_callback</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"p\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">else</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"nb\">None</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"p\">},</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p><code>T::HAS_READ</code> is true if the implementor of the trait has overriden the default implementation.<br>\nHere, <code>T</code> is the <code>Operations</code> trait</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Rust\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"cp\">#[vtable]</span>\n<span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">trait</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Operations</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>which defines some rust functions such as:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Rust\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"sd\">/// Creates a new instance of this file.</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"sd\">///</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"sd\">/// Corresponds to the `open` function pointer in `struct file_operations`.</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">fn</span> <span class=\"nf\">open</span><span class=\"p\">(</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"n\">fs_info</span>: <span class=\"o\">&lt;&lt;</span><span class=\"bp\">Self</span>::<span class=\"n\">Filesystem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">as</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">fs</span>::<span class=\"n\">Type</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span>::<span class=\"n\">Data</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">as</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ForeignOwnable</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span>::<span class=\"n\">Borrowed</span><span class=\"o\">&lt;'</span><span class=\"nb\">_</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"n\">context</span>: <span class=\"kp\">&amp;</span><span class=\"nc\">Self</span>::<span class=\"n\">OpenData</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"n\">file</span>: <span class=\"kp\">&amp;</span><span class=\"nc\">File</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span>-&gt; <span class=\"nb\">Result</span><span class=\"o\">&lt;</span><span class=\"bp\">Self</span>::<span class=\"n\">Data</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span><span class=\"p\">;</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Now a filesystem module could implement this trait and implement the open callback in rust.<br>\nFinally, the <code>open_callback</code> calls into this trait:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Rust\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">unsafe</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">extern</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s\">\"C\"</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">fn</span> <span class=\"nf\">open_callback</span><span class=\"p\">(</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"n\">inode</span>: <span class=\"o\">*</span><span class=\"k\">mut</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">bindings</span>::<span class=\"n\">inode</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"n\">file</span>: <span class=\"o\">*</span><span class=\"k\">mut</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">bindings</span>::<span class=\"n\">file</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span>-&gt; <span class=\"nc\">core</span>::<span class=\"n\">ffi</span>::<span class=\"n\">c_int</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"n\">from_result</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"o\">||</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"o\">..</span><span class=\"p\">.</span>\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"kd\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ptr</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">T</span>::<span class=\"n\">open</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">fs_info</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">unsafe</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">&amp;*</span><span class=\"n\">arg</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">},</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">fileref</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"o\">?</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">into_foreign</span><span class=\"p\">();</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>What I would like is to be able to specify somehow from Rust that I don't want to implement the callback myself, I want to use a generic C implementation. The <code>file_operations</code> VTABLE is a filesystem abstraction which is only defined once, so I cannot simply overwrite it with my desired C function.</p>",
        "id": 380372820,
        "sender_full_name": "Ariel Miculas",
        "timestamp": 1690814680
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>How about a <code>DefaultOperationSelection</code> trait?</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Rust\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">trait</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">DefaultOperationSelection</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">   </span><span class=\"k\">const</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">READ</span>: <span class=\"nb\">Option</span><span class=\"o\">&lt;</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"k\">unsafe</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">extern</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s\">\"C\"</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">fn</span><span class=\"p\">(</span>\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"n\">file</span>: <span class=\"o\">*</span><span class=\"k\">mut</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">bindings</span>::<span class=\"n\">file</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"n\">buf</span>: <span class=\"o\">*</span><span class=\"k\">mut</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">core</span>::<span class=\"n\">ffi</span>::<span class=\"n\">c_char</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"n\">len</span>: <span class=\"nc\">core</span>::<span class=\"n\">ffi</span>::<span class=\"n\">c_size_t</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"n\">offset</span>: <span class=\"o\">*</span><span class=\"k\">mut</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">bindings</span>::<span class=\"n\">loff_t</span>\n<span class=\"w\">         </span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span>-&gt; <span class=\"nc\">core</span>::<span class=\"n\">ffi</span>::<span class=\"n\">c_ssize_t</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nb\">None</span><span class=\"p\">;</span>\n<span class=\"w\">   </span><span class=\"o\">..</span><span class=\"p\">.</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>and </p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Rust\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"k\">impl</span><span class=\"o\">&lt;</span><span class=\"n\">A</span>: <span class=\"nc\">OpenAdapter</span><span class=\"o\">&lt;</span><span class=\"n\">T</span>::<span class=\"n\">OpenData</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">T</span>: <span class=\"nc\">Operations</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">DefaultOperationSelection</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">OperationsVtable</span><span class=\"o\">&lt;</span><span class=\"n\">A</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">const</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">VTABLE</span>: <span class=\"nc\">bindings</span>::<span class=\"n\">file_operations</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">bindings</span>::<span class=\"n\">file_operations</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"n\">open</span>: <span class=\"nb\">Some</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"bp\">Self</span>::<span class=\"n\">open_callback</span><span class=\"p\">),</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"n\">release</span>: <span class=\"nb\">Some</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"bp\">Self</span>::<span class=\"n\">release_callback</span><span class=\"p\">),</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"n\">read</span>: <span class=\"nc\">if</span><span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"o\">&lt;</span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">as</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Operations</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span>::<span class=\"n\">HAS_READ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"nb\">Some</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"bp\">Self</span>::<span class=\"n\">read_callback</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"p\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">else</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"o\">&lt;</span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">as</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">DefaultOperationSelection</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span>::<span class=\"n\">READ</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"p\">},</span>\n\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 380416460,
        "sender_full_name": "Boqun Feng",
        "timestamp": 1690821314
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This looks nice, but would it require the filesystem driver to have access to the <code>bindings</code> module? If I want to overwrite the default <code>llseek</code> with <code>generic_file_llseek</code> for example, I would need access to <code>bindings::generic_file_llseek</code>.</p>",
        "id": 380428010,
        "sender_full_name": "Ariel Miculas",
        "timestamp": 1690823384
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If a C filesystem driver wants to use generic_file_llseek, it will do the same thing right? Also you can access the <code>bindings</code> module via <code>kernel::bindings::...</code> I think</p>",
        "id": 380429171,
        "sender_full_name": "Boqun Feng",
        "timestamp": 1690823606
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ideally, the goal is that non-<code>kernel</code> code does not have access to <code>bindings</code>.</p>",
        "id": 380433484,
        "sender_full_name": "Miguel Ojeda",
        "timestamp": 1690824503
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(As usual, we may need an exception here or there, but the idea is that we provide ways to do whatever is commonly needed without direct access to the C side, and thus minimize the need for <code>unsafe</code> blocks too)</p>",
        "id": 380434015,
        "sender_full_name": "Miguel Ojeda",
        "timestamp": 1690824610
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>can't we just provide a safe wrapper for <code>generic_file_llseek</code>?</p>",
        "id": 380445390,
        "sender_full_name": "Benno Lossin",
        "timestamp": 1690826868
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's just a pointer to an <code>unsafe extern \"C\" fn(..)</code>, I don't think referencing it will add more unsafe blocks?</p>",
        "id": 380449432,
        "sender_full_name": "Boqun Feng",
        "timestamp": 1690827718
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"546447\">Benno Lossin</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/291565-Help/topic/C.20callbacks.20in.20vtables/near/380445390\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>can't we just provide a safe wrapper for <code>generic_file_llseek</code>?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Hmm, this seems convoluted to me, it would require an <code>llseek_callback</code> function which calls a user defined rust function which then calls the safe wrapper for <code>generic_file_llseek</code> which finally calls <code>generic_file_llseek</code>. And then I need to do the same for every generic filesystem function that one might want to use from rust.</p>",
        "id": 380456183,
        "sender_full_name": "Ariel Miculas",
        "timestamp": 1690829127
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>would it not just be this?</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Rust\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"cp\">#[vtable]</span>\n<span class=\"k\">impl</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Operations</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">for</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">MyOps</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">fn</span> <span class=\"nf\">llseek</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"o\">..</span><span class=\"p\">.)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"n\">kernel</span>::<span class=\"n\">fs</span>::<span class=\"n\">generic_file_llseek</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"o\">..</span><span class=\"p\">.)</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"p\">}</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 380456775,
        "sender_full_name": "Benno Lossin",
        "timestamp": 1690829260
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>yes, from the user perspective; maybe it could work like this, although it looks a little strange to go back and forth from C to Rust like this; thanks for the suggestion</p>",
        "id": 380458977,
        "sender_full_name": "Ariel Miculas",
        "timestamp": 1690829732
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So will <code>kernel::fs::generic_file_llseek</code> use the <code>bindings::generic_file_llseek</code> to implement or we just implement by ourselves? If we choose latter, we need a way to make sure they are equivalent (or we don't need? Because Rust defaults and C defaults can be different?)</p>",
        "id": 380459180,
        "sender_full_name": "Boqun Feng",
        "timestamp": 1690829776
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm assuming it's just a wrapper over <code>bindings::generic_file_llseek</code>, but it's not a problem because the kernel code has access to bindings. The user only calls the safe wrapper exported on the rust side.</p>",
        "id": 380460082,
        "sender_full_name": "Ariel Miculas",
        "timestamp": 1690829982
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>yes I thought it could just be a wrapper</p>",
        "id": 380461056,
        "sender_full_name": "Benno Lossin",
        "timestamp": 1690830172
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>One concern I have is not being able to go from the rust abstractions back to the C FFI.<br>\nFor example, the <code>read_callback</code> is defined like this:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Rust\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">unsafe</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">extern</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s\">\"C\"</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">fn</span> <span class=\"nf\">read_callback</span><span class=\"p\">(</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"n\">file</span>: <span class=\"o\">*</span><span class=\"k\">mut</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">bindings</span>::<span class=\"n\">file</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"n\">buf</span>: <span class=\"o\">*</span><span class=\"k\">mut</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">core</span>::<span class=\"n\">ffi</span>::<span class=\"n\">c_char</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"n\">len</span>: <span class=\"nc\">core</span>::<span class=\"n\">ffi</span>::<span class=\"n\">c_size_t</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"n\">offset</span>: <span class=\"o\">*</span><span class=\"k\">mut</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">bindings</span>::<span class=\"n\">loff_t</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span>-&gt; <span class=\"nc\">core</span>::<span class=\"n\">ffi</span>::<span class=\"n\">c_ssize_t</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>and the <code>read</code> function which the rust side needs to implement is defined like this:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Rust\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"sd\">/// Reads data from this file to the caller's buffer.</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"sd\">///</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"sd\">/// Corresponds to the `read` and `read_iter` function pointers in `struct file_operations`.</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">fn</span> <span class=\"nf\">read</span><span class=\"p\">(</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"n\">_data</span>: <span class=\"o\">&lt;</span><span class=\"bp\">Self</span>::<span class=\"n\">Data</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">as</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ForeignOwnable</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span>::<span class=\"n\">Borrowed</span><span class=\"o\">&lt;'</span><span class=\"nb\">_</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"n\">_file</span>: <span class=\"kp\">&amp;</span><span class=\"nc\">File</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"n\">_writer</span>: <span class=\"kp\">&amp;</span><span class=\"nc\">mut</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">impl</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">IoBufferWriter</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"n\">_offset</span>: <span class=\"kt\">u64</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span>-&gt; <span class=\"nb\">Result</span><span class=\"o\">&lt;</span><span class=\"kt\">usize</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"nb\">Err</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">EINVAL</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p><code>buf</code> and <code>len</code> have become <code>writer: &amp;mut impl IoBufferWriter</code>, which has a <code>len</code> method but there's no way to get back the original raw pointer. So I cannot call <code>generic_read_dir</code>, which requires these parameters:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Rust\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"n\">ssize_t</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">generic_read_dir</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"k\">struct</span> <span class=\"nc\">file</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">*</span><span class=\"n\">filp</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">char</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">__user</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">*</span><span class=\"n\">buf</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">size_t</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">siz</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">loff_t</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">*</span><span class=\"n\">ppos</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>(let's assume generic_read_dir does something useful with its parameters instead of returning -EISDIR)<br>\nOf course, I could allocate another buffer, but this adds additional overhead to what in C would be a simple assignment.</p>",
        "id": 380706622,
        "sender_full_name": "Ariel Miculas",
        "timestamp": 1690897555
    }
